    • pointIconSize

      @Nullable @PositiveOrZero(message="{validation.positiveOrZero}") @Max(value=300L, message="{validation.maxNumber}") private @PositiveOrZero(message="{validation.positiveOrZero}") @Max(value=300L,message="{validation.maxNumber}") java.lang.Integer pointIconSize
      Internally it will be represented as "scale" parameter from 0.0 to 3.0 unit with the step of 0.1. Where 1.0 is the scale of default window font. For User's convenience scale unit is represented as the percentage unit from 0 to 300(%) where 10% is "scale = '0.1'", 90% is "scale = '0.9'" etc.

    • pointIconOpacity

      @Nullable @PositiveOrZero(message="{validation.positiveOrZero}") @Max(value=100L, message="{validation.maxNumber}") private @PositiveOrZero(message="{validation.positiveOrZero}") @Max(value=100L,message="{validation.maxNumber}") java.lang.Integer pointIconOpacity

      For User's convenience it represents a percentage input as 0 - 100%.

      (Internally it will be converted into hexadecimal representation as 00 - FF (0 - 255).)

      This color tag is applied as an overlay to PNG icons, the #FFFFFF is the white color and won't affect the icons color, but the first hex "alpha channel" value will. (E.g. 00FFFFFF will make the icons invisible.)

      ********* FROM THE KML DOCUMENTATION ************************ Color and opacity (alpha) values are expressed in hexadecimal notation. The range of values for any one color is 0 to 255 (00 to ff). For alpha, 00 is fully transparent and ff is fully opaque. The order of expression is aabbggrr, where aa=alpha (00 to ff); bb=blue (00 to ff); gg=green (00 to ff); rr=red (00 to ff). For example, if you want to apply a blue color with 50 percent opacity to an overlay, you would specify the following: <color>7fff0000</color>, where alpha=0x7f, blue=0xff, green=0x00, and red=0x00

      Source: https://developers.google.com/kml/documentation/kmlreference#colorstyle **************************************************************

The order of expression is aabbggrr, where aa=alpha (00 to ff); bb=blue (00 to ff); gg=green (00 to ff); rr=red (00 to ff). For example, if you want to apply a blue color with 50 percent opacity to an overlay, you would specify the following: <color>7fff0000</color>, where alpha=0x7f, blue=0xff, green=0x00, and red=0x00

      Source: https://developers.google.com/kml/documentation/kmlreference#colorstyle **************************************************************

    • replaceLocusIcons

      private boolean replaceLocusIcons
      For POIs with included photos Locus creates icons on a map as thumbnails. For a better visibility you can change them all to a specific pictogram.

    • pictogramName

      @Nullable private java.lang.String pictogramName
      A full names of the existing pictograms in the 'resources/static/pictograms' directory. E.g. 'pictogram1.png', 'pictogram2.PNG' etc. This pictogram is intended to replace all the Locus photo thumbnails in placemarks.
